An <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" href="https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/press/pr/date/2018/html/ssm.pr180315.en.html">addendum</a>, issued in 2018, specified the time frame for lenders to set aside funds to cover nonperforming loans: two to seven years, depending on whether the loan was secured or not. As of 2020, eurozone lenders still have approximately $1 trillion worth of nonperforming loans on their books.

The <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/i/imf.asp">International Monetary Fund</a> (IMF) also sets out multiple criteria for a <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="2" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" href="https://www.imf.org/external/np/sta/fsi/eng/2003/051403bp.pdf">nonperforming loan classification</a>.

